ce:section.ce:para:
The crystal structure and crystallographic properties of as-prepared materials were characterized by X-ray diffraction (XRD) analysis, as exhibited in Fig. 3
                     a. All samples shared two typical diffraction peaks at 13.2° and 27.4°, corresponding to the (100) plane of interlayer stacking of the repeated heptazine network and the (002) reflection of the graphitic-like aromatic packing motifs, respectively [43,44]. The tri-s-triazine ring structure endows g-C3N4 with appealing electronic property, surface basicity, and chemical stability in harsh condition. The XRD profiles of D-CDs/CNNVS and A-CDs/CNNVS are significantly similar to that of pristine CNNVS, indicating that the original crystal structure of g-C3N4 is well preserved after the addition of D-CDs and A-CDs. Notably, the peak intensities of the (002) spacing for D-CDs/CNNVS and A-CDs/CNNVS were significantly enhanced and the peak positions showed the slight to the right with the addition of D-CDs and A-CDs, which may be attributed to the introduction of D-CDs/A-CDs, leading to larger crystal spacing, favoring the optimization of the optical properties, thermal stability, and interlayer charge transfer [45–48]. For the FT-IR spectra of as-prepared samples, as revealed in Fig. 3b, the characteristic peak at 812 cm−1 is the unique breathing vibration of heptazine ring in g-C3N4, and the peak at 1200–1650 cm−1 belongs to the stretching vibration mode of C-N/C = N heterocycles, while the peak at 2900 ∼ 3300 cm−1 is the caused by the stretching vibration of N-Hx (x = 1 or 2)[49,50]. Moreover, no new other peaks were generated in the FT-IR spectra of D-CDs/CNNVS and A-CDs/CNNVS, which may be due to the relatively limited content of D-CDs and A-CDs in the composite system [51]. The elemental composition and chemical state of CNNVS, D-CDs/CNNVS and A-CDs/CNNVS was further mensurated by means of X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) technology. As provided in Fig. 3c and Table S1, as-prepared samples consisted of three fundamental elements, including C, N and a small amount of O elements [52–54]. The addition of D-CDs elevated the C elemental content to 43.35 % compared to CNNVS (41.31 %). Notably, as A-CDs were introduce, the content of elemental C and O was further increased to 45.05 % and 3.33 %, which may be due to the fact that the conjugated π structure in the organic fluorophore molecules contain a large number of C atoms [55]. Fig. 3d demonstrates the C 1 s spectra of samples, convolving into three peaks (see Table S2), which are identical with C-C/C = C, C-O and N-C = N, respectively [56]. Remarkably, the binding energy of C-C/C = C and N-C = N for D-CDs/CNNVS and A-CDs/CNNVS shifted into a larger value compared to pristine CNNVS, proving that the introduction of the conjugate π-structures of D-CDs and A-CDs caused a transformation in electronic structure [57]. In Fig. 3e, the N 1 s spectra of as-prepared samples can be divided into four peaks for C-N = C, N-(C)3, C-N-H and π excitations, respectively (See Table S3) [58], and the loading of the D-CDs and A-CDs has a weak impact in the binding energy [59,60]. Fig. 3f reveals the O 1 s spectra and can be divided into two peaks (See Table S4), which have been assigned to O-H and C = O, respectively [61]. Compared to CNNVS, the peak intensity of O-H and C = O shared a significant increasement after the introduction of D-CDs/A-CDs, which may be ascribe to the effect of abundant oxygen-containing functional groups on the surface of D-CDs/A-CDs [62]. Upon the addition of A-CDs, the O 1 s spectrum mainly exhibits a significant increase in binding energy, which is due to the abundance of conjugated π-structural units in the fluorophore molecules, thereby affecting the electronic structure of the pristine CNNVS [63]. It is noteworthy that organic conjugated polymers formed by the repetitive attachment of a large number of conjugated structural units have not only favorable electrical conductivity, but have also been shown to have outstanding optical properties, such as light absorption in the UV–visible spectral range as well as fluorescent properties [64]. From the UV–Vis diffuse reflectance spectroscopy of prepared photocatalysts in Fig. 3g, it displays that a typical absorption band of the pristine CNNVS started at around 455 nm can be discovered [65–67]. A significant redshift of the absorption edges for D-CDs/CNNVS and A-CDs/CNNVS in the spectral range from 460 to 600 nm was clearly observed with the addition of D-CDs and A-CDs, which may be attributed to the interaction between the conjugated π-electron system of D-CDs/A-CDs and the electronic structure of CNNVS [68]. Compared to D-CDs/CNNVS, the absorption tail range of A-CDs/CNNVS expands from 500 to 700 nm, which is related to the fluorescence properties and the role of C = O functional groups of the fluorophore molecules [69]. The band gap (Eg
                     ) values of CNNVS, D-CDs/CNNVS and A-CDs/CNNVS were 2.85, 2.4 and 2.35 eV, respectively, which were determined via the UV–Vis diffuse reflectance spectral conversions (Fig. 3h) and calculated from the Kubelka-Munk function [70]. The value of the conduction band (CB) for as-prepared samples were confirmed via Mott-Schottky (M−S) curves and provided in Fig. S5, and the flat band potential determined as the x-intercept in the M−S diagram can be used to approximate and estimate the conduction band (CB) position [71,72]. After conversion, the CB positions of CNNVS, D-CDs/CNNVS and A-CDs/CNNVS are −0.48, −0.51 and −0.57 V, respectively. Compared to the CNNVS, there is a sharply negative shift of 0.9 V for A-CDs/CNNVS, while only minor difference for the D-CDs/CNNVS, illustrating that the presence of the fluorophore molecules in A-CDs/CNNVS is the hinge to enhance the proton reduction kinetics for photocatalytic water splitting into H2 due to the significant change for the optical properties and the band structures (Fig. 3i).
